<HL>
   General Homes
   Wins Clearance
   For Realignment
   ----
   By Christi Harlan
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8
</SO>
<CO>
   GHO
</CO>
<IN>
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
</IN>
<LP>
   General Homes Corp. obtained a court order allowing the
company to voluntarily reorganize under Chapter 11 of the
U.S. Bankruptcy Code, reversing its opposition to an
involuntary reorganization sought last month by three
bondholders.
   The Houston-based homebuilder set the stage for a
voluntary reorganization last week when it obtained a court
order allowing it to pay suppliers and contractors. The order
was a critical step toward preventing unpaid suppliers and
contractors from filing liens to block the sales of homes and
lots.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "We are entering this phase in about the best position we
can be in," said General Homes president W.A. LeSage. "There
shouldn't be a disruption in our business."
   As recently as two weeks ago, Mr. LeSage had said General
Homes would seek to dismiss the involuntary Chapter 11
petition filed against the company July 11 by three
bondholders.
   Yesterday, Mr. LeSage said the involuntary reorganization
created "a lot of uncertainty" for the company and that
voluntary reorganization "made a lot of sense."
   "This should be an opportunity to finally restructure this
company," Mr. LeSage said.
   The company had been struggling for three years to
overcome losses on its portfolio of raw land, whose value
plummeted in the Texas real estate depression.
   The Texas real estate market is now showing signs of
recovery, particularly in the Houston area, where most of
General Homes' land holdings are located. The company also
holds real estate in the Dallas-Fort Worth area; Orlando,
Fla.; and Phoenix, Ariz.
   "The land, at this point, is an asset that could bring
value to the company," Mr. LeSage said.
   General Homes currently owes about $225 million to its
senior secured lenders, who hold liens on all of the
company's real estate assets. The principal amount of the
company's subordinated debt is about $140 million.
   The voluntary Chapter 11 petition doesn't affect the
company's units, including a title company and a mortgage
subsidiary, Mr. LeSage said.
   General Homes is represented in the reorganization by the
Houston-based law firm of Sheinfeld, Maley &amp; Kay.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900815-0118
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900815-0118.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Abreast of the Market:
   Stock Prices Edge Up 0.99 Point
   As Mideast Tensions Seem to Ease
   ----
   By David Wilson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C2
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Drawing strength from indications that
tensions in the Middle East could be easing, the stock market
bounced back from early weakness and ended higher despite a
late sell-off.
   However, trading was light as skepticism about whether the
Persian Gulf conflict will be resolved anytime soon and
ongoing concerns about its economic impact damped interest.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "It's a little bit early to get excited," said Larry
Greenwald, a block trader at Sanford C. Bernstein &amp; Co. The
market's sluggish pace "indicates that people are waiting to
see what the next move is going to be," he said.
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average, which swung within a
trading range of more than 30 points over the course of the
session, closed 0.99 higher at 2747.77.
   Broader measures, which trailed badly Monday as the Dow
Jones industrials advanced 30.20, fared a bit better than the
30-stock measure in the latest session. Standard &amp; Poor's
500-Stock Index gained 0.55 to 339.39, the New York Stock
Composite Index rose 0.47 to 186.10 and the Dow Jones Equity
Market Index added 0.51 to 314.55.
   Advancing issues topped decliners on the Big Board by 852
to 640. Volume amounted to 130,320,000 shares, up from
122,820,000 Monday but well below the totals set earlier this
month when prices plummeted. "There's just a lot of waiting
and seeing going on here," said Robert S. Robbins, a market
strategist and technical analyst at Robinson-Humphrey Co.,
Atlanta.
   Stocks drifted back to their session lows at midmorning,
but then started to recover amid news that King Hussein of
Jordan was on his way to meet with President Bush a day after
holding talks with Iraqi President Saddam Hussein.
   Flurries of program buying resulting from stock-index
arbitrage fueled the market's rise, traders said. The
programs were triggered when index futures rallied to sharp
premiums to the cash indexes, allowing program traders to
lock in profits by selling index-futures contracts and buying
baskets of stocks.
   Prices peaked in the final hour of trading as the
arbitrage buying ran its course, and the market came under
selling pressure near the close. The industrial average
erased gains of about 15 points and stood slightly lower just
before the session ended.
   Mr. Robbins said the market is going through what he
called "a smoke clearing" following Iraq's occupation of
Kuwait. "We've got more inflation, and we've got the threat
of a mild recession," he said.
   But he noted that prices rebounded after falling about 10%
from their highs -- in line with most of the market's
pullbacks in the past few years. "We could get a bounce all
the way up to 2850 on the Dow {industrials}," he said.
   The Dow Jones Transportation Average fell 11.13 to 967.70
as airline issues were hit with selling, especially AMR,
which lost 2 1/8 to 49 on about double its average Big Board
composite daily volume.
   First Boston analyst Paul Karos told Dow Jones
Professional Investor Report he will lower his 1990 and 1991
earnings estimates sharply on AMR, citing
weaker-than-expected business at its American Airlines unit.
Mr. Karos declined to specify his new estimates.
   AMR acknowledged that it has been reducing its
expectations for air traffic growth, based on advance booking
levels. "We don't know how much" the growth will drop off,
said AMR spokesman Tim Smith. Shortly after the close, the
company said it would cut certain fares by 15% to 40%; Trans
World Airlines and Eastern Airlines lowered their fares
Monday.
   UAL, the parent company of United Airlines, fell 4 3/8 to
105 3/4 after postponing a planned 5.3% fare increase,
designed to offset higher fuel costs. Delta Air Lines dropped
1 7/8 to 57 1/2.
   Advanced Micro Devices rose 1/4 to 6 on 1.5 million
shares, reflecting speculation that the company may obtain
the right to manufacture its own version of Intel's 80386
microprocessor. The companies' dispute over the issue is now
in arbitration, and a decision is due next month.
   Bear Stearns &amp; Co. analyst Monroe I. Neff cited the
potential for Advanced Micro to win the case for cutting
Intel's investment rating to "hold" from "buy," according to
the investor report. Intel, which also was removed from the
firm's list of recommended issues, fell 1 1/4 to 37 and was
the most active issue traded on the Nasdaq National Market
System.
   General Motors added 5/8 to 40 1/8 after reaching a
tentative settlement with the United Auto Workers union of a
strike at a parts plant in Michigan. The walkout had forced a
full or partial shutdown of five GM assembly plants.
   May Department Stores rose 1 5/8 to 46 5/8. Other
retailing issues also moved higher as the market digested
quarterly reports; Tiffany rose 1 1/8 to 39 1/8, TJX climbed
1 1/8 to 15 and Waban gained 3/4 to 7 3/4.
   On the other hand, J.C. Penney fell 2 to 48 1/2 following
its fiscal second-quarter earnings report, which showed that
net income declined 15% from the year-earlier level. Analysts
had generally forecast that earnings would be about even with
a year ago.
   Sotheby's Holdings, whose second-quarter earnings were in
line with expectations, added 3/4 to 13 1/4. Net income
climbed 26% from a year earlier.
   Hanson rose 3/4 to 20 3/8. The British company posted a
27% increase in pretax profit for the nine months ended in
June.
   Avnet added 1 to 24 1/2 after its board authorized the
repurchase of up to one million common shares, representing
about 2.8% of its shares outstanding.
   Marion Merrell Dow went up 1 7/8 to 31 1/2. The company
increased its quarterly dividend by one-third, to 20 cents a
share.
   Cineplex Odeon, which said there is "substantial
uncertainty" about whether a proposed sale of 38 movie
theaters for $31.75 million will be completed, fell 1/2 to 3
1/8. Also, the company reported a second-quarter loss that
was only slightly narrower than its loss from continuing
operations a year earlier.
   The American Stock Exchange Market Value Index rose 1.94
to 339.94. Volume totaled 15,770,000 shares.
</TEXT>
