<DOCNO>
WSJ900815-0115
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900815-0115.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Something Tells Us the Committee
   Shouldn't Use the U.S. as a Model
   ----
   By Clay Chandler
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN
</CO>
<LP>
   TOKYO -- What's a hot conversational topic at Japan's
Ministry of International Trade and Industry?
   Well, table settings. "Is it right to put Lenox china on
the same table with traditional Japanese lacquerware?"
wonders Akio Tanaka, division director at MITI, the
no-nonsense bureaucracy better known for pondering how to
build faster computers and export more automobiles. "What
settings are best for French foods?"
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In a recently released report, "Vision for the 1990s,"
MITI promised to give this hard-driving country a better
quality of life. Now the ministry is making good on that
pledge with a bold new initiative focusing on the nation's
table manners.
   MITI officials have commissioned a committee of business
and government executives to develop and promote "new ways of
dining and communicating." The committee's formal mandate is
to exchange ideas about expanding Japan's leisure and service
industries. But Mr. Tanaka, who is responsible for the
project, says the group is also a forum for discussing ways
to help Japanese consumers shed their image as nouveau riche
and become more cosmopolitan and genteel.
   MITI officials are asking companies in the food and
beverage, tableware, hotel and other industries to help the
ministry raise Japan's cultural and culinary sensitivities.
"We want to make sure that the Japanese know how to use good
products, not just make them," Mr. Tanaka says.
   The group also wants to promote the proper mix of party
guests and is looking for ways to get more women and
foreigners invited to social gatherings in Japan, Mr. Tanaka
says.
   If the project's kick-off party is any indication, the
ministry has a way to go. Gesturing apologetically around the
banquet hall at dripping ice sculptures and clusters of
blue-suited, beer-drinking Japanese businessmen, Mr. Tanaka
concedes: "Of course, this reception is rather conventional."
   The committee's first item of business when it convenes
next month will be to draft a questionnaire for housewives so
as to learn more about Japanese dining habits. Mr. Tanaka
hopes that data will help MITI and the panel to gain greater
insight into how Japanese households communicate. "Eating and
talking are activities that have always gone together," he
says.
   Let's see, isn't that known as talking with your mouth
full?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900815-0114
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900815-0114.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Edgell Offers Plan
   To Its Bondholders
   For Debt Payments
   ----
   By Patrick M. Reilly
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   X.EDG GE
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
BUYBACKS, REDEMPTIONS, SWAP OFFERS (BBK)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Edgell Communications Inc., the former unit of
Harcourt Brace Jovanovich Inc. taken private in a management
buy-out in 1987, has offered its bondholders and creditors a
plan to restructure debt payments.
   The exchange offer from New Century Communications Inc.,
the New York-based parent holding company of Edgell
Communications, follows a deteriorating situation at the
publishing and trade show company. Founder Robert Edgell
unexpectedly resigned in March as chief executive. And the
company did not make a $7 million interest payment to
bondholders on July 16.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Cleveland-based Edgell, one of the country's largest trade
magazine publishers and a growing force in the trade
exposition field, continues to operate with substantial
profit margins, Edgell executives said. But revenue from
magazines and trade shows have not grown as expected, and the
company can't keep up with interest payments.
   Richard B. Swank, the recently appointed chief executive
officer of Edgell, said that as part of the restructuring
plan, as many as eight Edgell magazines have been pegged for
sale.
   Edgell Communications was formed in 1987, when Mr. Edgell
led management in a $334.1 million leveraged buy-out of the
business publications and school supplies unit of Harcourt
Brace. The buy-out was financed by Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co., a
unit of General Electric Co., and General Electric Capital
Corp., another GE unit, which remains the majority owner of
Edgell. Traditionally profitable but unglamorous, Edgell's
trade magazines include Urology Times, Pipeline &amp; Gas
Journal, and Food Management, as well as 52 other titles.
   In the exchange offer made last week, Edgell is proposing
a change in the amortization schedule on a $185 million loan
from General Electric Credit Corp. Edgell is asking that
interest payments on the loan be delayed and spread out over
a period of time. Edgell is also proposing that institutions
that own about $100 million in high-yield junk bonds exchange
their bonds for equity in the company. Edgell's buy-out was
also backed by $5 million from private investors, as well as
about $8 million in cash and $45 million in preferred shares
from Kidder, Peabody.
   The deadline for the exchange offer is Aug. 30. Neither
Kidder nor General Electric would comment on the exchange
offers.
   Edgell is still a "good company," Mr. Swank said, which he
claimed has operating profit margins of more than 20% in
magazines and more than 35% in the trade show business.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900815-0113
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900815-0113.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Technology &amp; Medicine:
   New Treatment
   For AIDS Seen
   As Promising
   ----
   By Ron Winslow
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8
</SO>
<IN>
MEDICAL AND BIOTECHNOLOGY (MTC)
</IN>
<GV>
FOOD AND DRUG ADMINISTRATION (FDA)
</GV>
<LP>
   Medical researchers said a new approach to treating an
intermediate form of acquired immune deficiency syndrome
showed promise in a preliminary clinical trial involving five
patients.
   The significance of the findings was unclear because so
few patients were studied and because of other limitations in
the trial, including lack of a control group. Indeed, editors
of Annals of Internal Medicine, where the study appears in
the current issue, cautioned that it leaves "substantial
questions" unanswered. But they decided to publish the
results anyway because "AIDS is a calamitous illness" and
"positive results were reported for a treatment unique for an
infectious disease." The Food and Drug Administration has
approved the approach for further study.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The treatment is called photopheresis. In the process, a
sample of a patient's blood is separated into red and white
blood cells after the patient takes a light-sensitive drug
called 8-methoxypsoralen. Then the white blood cells are
exposed to ultraviolet-A radiation and returned to the body.
   The five patients -- three homosexual men and two
intravenous drug users, one female -- were treated twice
monthly for up to 15 months. All were diagnosed as having
AIDS-related complex, or ARC, a condition preliminary to
full-blown AIDS and characterized by fatigue, swollen lymph
nodes and diminished counts of infection-fighting T-cells.
None of the patients had previous therapy for AIDS.
   Four of the patients were significantly improved after six
months both in subjective reports of physical well-being and
in certain objective blood chemistry indicators. One of the
improved patients voluntarily halted treatment after five
months, but continued to be evaluated during the course of
the study. Encouraging results continued in the other three
for up to 15 months. One patient, the woman with a history of
drug abuse, didn't respond to the treatment.
   The researchers aren't sure how the treatment works, but
believe that it inactivates the AIDS virus, thus preventing
its ability to infect other cells. A similar procedure has
proved beneficial in treating T-cell lymphoma, a cancer of
the lymphatic system.
   "The results are encouraging but must be viewed with
extreme caution," says Emil Bisaccia, medical director of the
photopheresis unit at Morristown Memorial Hospital in
Morristown, N.J., where the research was done, and an
assistant professor of medicine at Columbia University
College of Physicians and Surgeons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
