900815-0045.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Chrysler Discusses Linkups
   With 3 European Firms
</HL>
<DATE>
08/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   C F.RNA VOLVY FIA
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   WINDSOR, Ont. -- Chrysler Corp. chairman Lee A. Iacocca
said the auto maker has discussed potential ties with three
European manufacturers, but said there won't be an agreement
within the next month and dismissed the possibility of a
full-scale merger.
   Mr. Iacocca, speaking at a plant ceremony marking the
start of production for the 1991 minivans, said Chrysler has
talked with Regie Nationale des Usines Renault of France,
Volvo AB of Sweden and Fiat S.p.A. of Italy. He also said
Chrysler has talked with several other auto companies about
possible arrangements.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The negotiations with Fiat have sparked speculation in
Europe and the U.S. that the Italian company may agree to
distribute Chrysler products in Europe, help Chrysler develop
new vehicles or, possibly, buy a sizable equity stake in
Chrysler.
   Mr. Iacocca said an equity stake by another auto maker in
Chrysler isn't imminent, but may come in the future.
   The company later clarified Mr. Iacocca's comments about
Renault and Volvo talks, saying those discussions primarily
involve "commercial arrangements."
   Chrysler shares fell 12.5 cents yesterday to $13.125 in
composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
   "Everybody's talking to everybody," Mr. Iacocca said. "I
think over time everybody's going to need some kind of
affiliation or partnership."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900815-0044
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900815-0044.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   J.C. Penney Net
   Was Down 15%
   In Second Quarter
   ----
   By Kevin Helliker
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
08/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   JCP MA
</CO>
<IN>
BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   DALLAS -- J.C. Penney Co., reporting a
larger-than-expected 15% drop in second-quarter earnings,
blamed the decline on a weak economy that company officials
and industry observers fear is growing weaker.
   Penney earnings dropped to $83 million, or 63 cents a
share, from $98 million, or 74 cents a share, the year
earlier. Revenue rose a meager 4.5%, to $3.83 billion from
$3.67 billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Penney attributed the earnings decline primarily to slack
consumer demand -- a problem likely to worsen in light of
what's happened since July 28, when Penney's second quarter
ended. "Rising prices at the pump mean that consumers have
reduced spending power," said Ira Silver, Penney's chief
economist.
   Not only that, Mr. Silver said, but higher energy prices
resulting from the Mideast crisis "clearly affect a lot of
things J.C. Penney sells -- synthetic clothes, sneakers, any
product with an oil-related content."
   With the costs of those products likely to rise, Mr.
Silver said the company is in a bind. "There is pressure for
price increases" on Penney products, he said. But if, for
instance, the company raises the price of a sweater, "our
(fear) is, nobody's going to buy it," he said, because "the
economy is weak."
   Analysts, aware that many retailers experienced soft sales
in May and June, expected a decline in Penney's
second-quarter earnings, but not of such magnitude. "It was
several cents below what I expected," said N. Richard Nelson
Jr. of Duff &amp; Phelps, who in response lowered his year-end
earnings projections for Penney to $6.25 a share from $6.50.
   The market responded by skewering the stock, which dropped
$2 to close yesterday at $48.50 in New York Stock Exchange
composite trading.
   The economy wasn't entirely to blame. "Dillards, Limited,
the Gap, Dayton Hudson, are doing all right," asserted Edward
Weller, retailer analyst at Montgomery Securities. But
compared with those chains, Penney, which is trying to evolve
from a frumpy mass merchant to a trendy specialty retailer,
lacks clear focus and a sharp image, according to some
observers. "Penney is improving its image, but it still has a
ways to go," said Mr. Nelson.
   In a weakening economy, completing its repositioning could
become all the more difficult. "It's harder to make changes
when the economy goes soft," said Mr. Weller, adding that
Penney is "caught midstream."
   Penney Chairman William R. Howell acknowledged that the
company's repositioning contributed to the disappointing
quarter. "As we bring our merchandise in line with an
appropriate department store mix, we are temporarily giving
up some volume in conservative women's sportswear," he said.
   But he added that "neither the refining of our merchandise
mix nor the costs associated with the development of new
specialty businesses would be particularly felt if the
economic climate were more favorable."
   For the six months ended July 28, Penney said its earnings
rose 5% to $237 million, or $1.84 a share, from $226 million,
or $1.71 a share, the year earlier. Six-month revenue rose
5.4% to $7.64 billion from $7.24 billion.
   Separately, May Department Stores Co. said net income in
the fiscal second quarter, ended Aug. 4, was flat with
year-earlier results of $78 million. However, earnings per
share rose 5% to 58 cents from 55 cents because fewer shares
are now outstanding. And earnings from continuing operations
-- excluding May's discontinued discount store units --
increased a more robust 10% to $78 million from $71 million a
year earlier.
   The St. Louis-based retailer said sales rose 9% to $2.19
billion from $2.04 billion a year earlier.
   The results, which were in line with analysts'
expectations, sent May shares up $1.625 to close at $46.625
in composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange. "Some
people are probably selling J.C. Penney and buying May," said
Mr. Weller of Montgomery Securities.
   ---
   Francine Schwadel in Chicago contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
