<HL>
   Business Brief -- Chiron Corp.:
   First-Ever Profit Is Posted,
   $3.4 Million for 2nd Period
</HL>
<DATE>
08/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   CHIR
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Chiron Corp., marking its first profitable period ever,
posted second-quarter net income of $3.4 million, or 20 cents
a share, compared with a year-earlier loss of $4.1 million,
or 30 cents a share.
   Buoyed by strong diagnostic business and increased product
sales, the Emeryville, Calif., biotechnology company's
revenue nearly doubled to $17.7 million from $9.2 million in
last year's second quarter. Chiron's bottom line also
benefited from the stabilization of research and development
expenses and other costs.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   For the six months, Chiron posted a narrowed loss of $1.2
million, or 8 cents a share, compared with a year-ago
sixmonth loss of nearly $9 million or 68 cents a share. The
1990 results include first-quarter charges of $9.8 million
for technology acquisition, and $1 million in costs for
postponement of a planned manufacturing facility, Chiron
said.
   Leading the company's turnaround was profit from its
diagnostics joint venture with the Ortho Diagnostics unit of
Johnson &amp; Johnson, the company said. Performance was also
buoyed by increased sales of Chiron's opthalmic products.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900815-0012
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900815-0012.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Consolidated Freightways Unit
</HL>
<DATE>
08/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   CNF
</CO>
<IN>
TRUCKING (TRK)
</IN>
<LP>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. -- CF Motor Freight, a unit of
Consolidated Freightways Inc., said it asked the Interstate
Commerce Commission to approve a fuel surcharge to offset the
sudden oil price increases touched off by the Middle East oil
crisis.
   If the federal agency approves the surcharge, it would be
effective Friday.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In a letter to its customers, CF Motor Freight said that,
if approved, the surcharge would initially add 1% to the cost
of shipments of less than a truckload, and 3.47% to
full-truckload shipments. They would change weekly, however,
based on the fluctuating cost of fuel.
   The surcharge is described as a straight pass-through of
increased costs, and it would be suspended when costs return
to normal, Consolidated Freightways said.
   Consolidated Freightways is a trucking and air freight
company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900815-0011
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900815-0011.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
08/15/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   VENEZUELA BACKED off from indications that it would
increase oil exports. Saudi Arabia still hasn't substantially
boosted its output, but said it is committed to do so. The
U.S. was counting on both nations to offset the loss of Iraqi
and Kuwaiti crude. Meanwhile, British Petroleum said it could
produce 200,000 more barrels a day from Alaska.
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. offered to mediate between Chevron and a
California county in a dispute holding up production of
100,000 barrels a day in oil.
   ---
   The FDIC proposed boosting banks' deposit insurance fees
by $1.1 billion next year to help ensure that it can cover
future bank failures.
   ---
   More airlines slashed certain fares, and several carriers
delayed any fuel-related ticket-price rises.
   ---
   Bush accused Democrats of breaking a pledge to offer a
deficit-cutting plan and vowed to veto any bill that "busts
the budget." The Democrats denied making such a promise.
   ---
   The dollar fell against major currencies, reaching a
record low against the mark. Stocks and bonds edged higher.
Equities in Tokyo rebounded Tuesday after Monday's plunge.
   ---
   The price of gold has risen 7% in the past three days, to
$411.50 an ounce, and further tension in the Mideast could
push it even higher.
   ---
   Retail sales edged up 0.1% in July, after rising 1.1% in
June and falling the three previous months. Last month's flat
performance preceded the rise in oil prices, which could lead
consumers to curb their spending.
   ---
   Margin calls by brokers are increasing in frequency amid
the stock market's decline this month.
   ---
   Sales of North American-made cars and trucks dropped 18.5%
in early August. Industry officials are pessimistic about the
rest of 1990.
   ---
   GM and Ford are raising car prices aggressively in what
could be a boon to their Japanese rivals.
                                                                                                       

   GM agreed to strong job security guarantees to end a local
strike. The pact could be model for GM and UAW.
   ---
   Wheeling-Pittsburgh reached a tentative labor accord that
would give workers 11% of the steelmaker and allow it to
emerge from Chapter 11.
   ---
   Goldman Sachs named Robert E. Rubin and Stephen Friedman
to be senior partners and co-chairmen. They succeed John L.
Weinberg.
   ---
   Limited Inc.'s second-quarter profit rose 24% to $79
million, as sales jumped 17%. But the quickly expanding
retailer's same-store sales fell an estimated 5% in June and
July.
   ---
   AmBase agreed to sell its troubled insurance unit to
European investor group Vik Brothers for $544 million.
   ---
   Pepsi is expected to name David Wozak as its top marketer.
He is now marketing chief at the Pizza Hut unit.
   ---
   Cineplex Odeon's shares sank 15% after the Toronto cinema
concern said it may not be able to complete the sale of some
U.S. theater assets.
   ---
   General Homes won court approval to reorganize under
Chapter 11. The home builder had opposed an involuntary
reorganization sought last month by three bondholders.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 130,320,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2747.77, up 0.99; transportation 967.70, off 11.13; utilities
204.48, up 0.51.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3378.35, up
8.08.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 133.95, up 0.54; spot
index 133.50, up 0.95.
   Dollar: 148.78 yen, off 1.62; 1.5645 marks, off 0.0120.
   ---
   Corrections &amp; Amplifications
                                                                                                       

   LIMITED Inc. aims to be a $10 billion-a-year company with
10% after-tax profits by the mid-1990s. In some editions
yesterday, the percentage of the profit margin was misstated.
Also, Limited's same-store sales increased 5% in June and 6%
in July. In yesterday's What's News column, it was
incorrectly stated that same-store sales fell in those
months.
   (WSJ Aug. 16, 1990)
</TEXT>
